{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Display Property","slug":"css-display-property","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Box Model"],"learning_objectives":["Understand the Display property","Difference between block and inline","Understand inline-block","Understand display: none"],"theory":"The `display` property is the most important CSS property for controlling layout.\n\n*   `block`: Starts on a new line and takes up the full width (e.g., `<div>`, `<h1>`, `<p>`).\n*   `inline`: Takes only as much width as necessary and does NOT start on a new line (e.g., `<span>`, `<a>`). Width/height properties don't work.\n*   `inline-block`: Like inline, but you CAN set width/height.\n*   `none`: Hides the element completely.","syntax":"li {\n  display: inline;\n}\n\nimg {\n  display: block;\n}","examples":[{"code":".nav-link {\n  display: inline-block;\n  width: 100px;\n  height: 50px;\n}","output":"Links appearing side-by-side but with specific dimensions.","explanation":"Useful for navigation menus where you want clickable areas to be specific sizes."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Setting width on inline elements","correction":"`width`, `height`, `margin-top`, `margin-bottom` do NOT work on `display: inline` elements.","example":"Change to display: inline-block or block."}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What is the difference between `display: none` and `visibility: hidden`?","answer":"`display: none` removes the element from the document flow (no space). `visibility: hidden` hides it but occupies the same space.","difficulty":"Important"},{"question":"When would you use `inline-block`?","answer":"When you want elements side-by-side (like text) but need to control their dimensions (padding/margin/width).","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Hide an element with id='secret' so it takes no space.","hint":"Use display property.","solution":"#secret { display: none; }","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Responsive Menus","description":"On mobile, a menu might be `display: none` until a hamburger button is clicked (Javascript toggles it to `display: block`).","code":".mobile-menu.open { display: block; }"}],"exam_notes":["Every HTML element has a default display value (usually block or inline).","Flex and Grid are also values of the display property."],"summary":"Understanding `display` is the key to understanding how elements position themselves on the page.","order":13},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"css-introduction","path":"content/css/css-introduction.json","title":"Introduction to CSS","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","description":"","order":1},{"slug":"css-syntax","path":"content/css/css-syntax.json","title":"CSS Syntax","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"css-best-practices","path":"content/css/css-best-practices.json","title":"CSS Best Practices","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","description":"","order":3},{"slug":"css-borders","path":"content/css/css-borders.json","title":"CSS Borders","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","description":"","order":4},{"slug":"css-colors","path":"content/css/css-colors.json","title":"CSS Colors","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","description":"","order":5},{"slug":"css-backgrounds","path":"content/css/css-backgrounds.json","title":"CSS Backgrounds","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","description":"","order":6},{"slug":"css-comments","path":"content/css/css-comments.json","title":"CSS Comments","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","description":"","order":7},{"slug":"css-interview","path":"content/css/css-interview.json","title":"CSS Interview Preparation","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","description":"","order":8},{"slug":"css-margins","path":"content/css/css-margins.json","title":"CSS Margins","category":"Web Development","subject":"CSS","descrip